nd dysfunctional, highly secular societies are healthier, safer, greener, less violent, and more democratic and egalitarian than highly religious ones.Society without God provides a rich portrait of life in a secular society, exploring how a culture without faith copes with death, grapples with the meaning of life, and remains content through everyday ups and downs. This updated edition incorporates new data from recent studies, updated statistics, and a revised Introduction, as well as framing around the now more highly developed field of secular studies. It addresses the dramatic surge of irreligion in the United States and the rise of the “nones,” and adds data on societal health in specific US states, along with fascinating context regarding which are the most religious and which the most secular.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aReligion and sociology. 0aReligionvControversial literature. 7aRELIGION / Agnosticism.2bisacsh  aApostasy.  aAsatru.  aAtheism.  aBelief.  aBenign indifference.  aChristianity.  aCultural Religion.  aDanish culture.  aDanish history.  aDeath.  aDenmark.  aGeorge W. Bush.  aInternational Comparisons.  aJews.  aMeaning of Life.  aReligion.  aReligious Belief.  aReligious People.  aReluctance.  aReticence.  aRituals.  aScandinavia.  aScandinavian society.  aSecular Studies.  aSecular.  aSecularism.  aSecularity.  aSecularization.  aSocietal Well-being.  aSociological Theories.  aSweden.  aUnited States.  aUtter obliviousness.  aValues Voters.  aWell-being.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479891856.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479891856423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479891856/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLT